{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"99053227-0375-4adf-9524-4d0c23f865ee","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update, since the existing workload versions are now out of sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't bring them up to date with a newer SDK.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, check that the required workload is actually installed with `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fbdfa439-b663-4ad0-bbd6-23559fb9cc31","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n**`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the new SDK.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** — Reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or incomplete installations. It doesn't update them to newer versions.\n\n\nThe right move is `dotnet workload update` since the SDK changed and the workloads need to sync with it — `repair` would just put back the old mismatched versions.","outputTokens":366,"requestId":"F3C1:1A8A2F:1ED145F:2298A1C:69E81955"},"id":"46a79ea0-c894-4a91-810e-d55346542edd","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:42:06.734Z","parentId":"9d396dc7-209c-4320-9a77-54c3f66c0d9b"}
